This test will check that lxqt-runner can launch applications. 

<dl>
    <dt> Press alt+f2  as the default shortcut to launch lxqt-runner</dt>
        <dd> lxqt-runner launches and is focused above all other windows. </dd>
    <dt> type qter into lxqt-runner. </dt>
        <dd> lxqt-runner offer to launch qterminal as both a drop down temrinal and and Qterminal by itself</dd> 
    <dt> Use the primary mouse button to click on the x button on lxqt-runner </dt>
        <dd> lxqt-runner closes returning your desktop to the previous state.</dd>
    <dt> press alt+f2 again to bring lxqt-runner back up again</dt>
        <dd> lxqt-runner reappears with qter and showing the two main options for lxqt-runner. </dd>
    <dt> Press the down arrow key to select the non drop down version of qterminal </dt>
        <dd> The drop down qterminal option not selected in lxqt-runner and qterminal is selected.</dd> 
    <dt> Press the enter button to launch qterminal. </dt> 
        <dd> lxqt-runner closes and a window of qterminal opens. </dd>
</dl>

This test will check lxqt-runner can use customized commands and save the history for your customized commands.

<dl>
    <dt> Press alt+f2 to open lxqt-runner and type pcmanfm-qt /etc</dt>
        <dd> lxqt-runner closes  pcmanfm-qt opens to the /etc directory</dd> 
    <dt> type pcmanfm-qt into the lxqt-runner </dt>
        <dd> lxqt-runner offers an option for pcmanfm-qt and an option to run pcmanfm-qt /etc from the directory</dd>
    <dt> Click file close for pcmanfm-qt </dt>
        <dd>  the pcmanfm-qt window closes </dd>     
    <dt> click on the provided optoin for pcmanfm-qt /etc </dt>
        <dd> pcmanfm-qt opens back to the /etc directory</dd> 
</dl>

